<section label="if-method">
	<title> Integrating Factor Method </title>	

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Let's now bring everything together into a clear, repeatable process. First with a recap, then a step-by-step guide to the <term>Integrating Factor Method</term> and finally, a series of examples that show how to apply this method to solve first-order linear differential equations.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<paragraphs label="if-integrating-factor-recap">
		<title> Method Steps </title>

		<p>
			Before jumping into the official method, let's recap the story so far ...
		</p>

		<p>
			<sidebyside widths="5% 5% 90%" valign="top">
				<p/><p>üìå</p>
				<p><em>All</em> first-order linear differential equation have a <xref ref="if-standard-form" text="custom"><term>standard form</term></xref>.</p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside widths="5% 5% 90%" valign="top">
				<p/><p>üìå</p>
				<p>Once in standard form, the equation can be multiplied by an <xref ref="if-standard-form" text="custom"><term>integrating factor</term></xref> to <q>complete a product rule</q> on the left-hand side.</p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside widths="5% 5% 90%" valign="top">
				<p/><p>üìå</p>
				<p>A <q>Complete product rule</q> is a sum of two terms that can be grouped inside a single derivative via a reversed product rule.</p>
			</sidebyside>
		</p>

		<p>
			More concretely, the process was broken down in a previous example as follows:
		</p>

		<p>
			<sidebyside valign="middle" widths="27% 33% 28%" margins="6% 6%">
				<p>Standard Form:</p>
				<p><me>\frac{dy}{dx} + 2 y = 5</me></p>
				<p><m>\leftarrow</m> Find &amp; Multiply by <m>e^{2x}</m></p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside valign="middle" widths="27% 33% 28%" margins="6% 6%">
				<p>Complete Product Rule:</p>
				<p><me>e^{2x}\frac{dy}{dx}	+ 2e^{2x} y = 5e^{2x}</me></p>
				<p><m>\leftarrow</m> Reverse Product Rule</p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside valign="middle" widths="27% 33% 28%" margins="6% 6%">
				<p>Grouped Derivative:</p>
				<p><me>\frac{d}{dx} \left[e^{2x} y \right] = 5e^{2x}</me></p>
				<p><m>\leftarrow</m> Direct Integration</p>
			</sidebyside>
		</p>

		<p>
			This essentially outlines the complete the complete integrating factor method process.
		</p>

		<exploration xml:id="if-method">
			<title> Integrating Factor (IF) Method </title>
			<p>
				Given a first-order linear equation in standard form:
			</p>

			<men xml:id="if-steps-standard-form">
				y' + P(x) y = Q(x),
			</men>

			<p>
				the general solution can be found through the following <em>three-step process</em>:
			</p>

			<dl width="narrow">
				<li xml:id="if-step-1"><title> Step 1: Find the Integrating Factor </title>

					<p>
						Identify <m>P(x)</m> and compute the <em>integrating factor</em>:
					</p>

					<p>
						<me>
							\mu = e\vphantom{\large|}^{\textstyle\int P(x)\ dx}
						</me>.
					</p>
					
				</li>
				<li xml:id="if-step-2"><title> Step 2: Multiply by <m>\mu</m> to Complete the Product Rule </title>
					<p>
						Multiply both sides of equation <xref ref="if-steps-standard-form"/> by <m>\mu</m> and reverse the product rule on the left side.
					</p>

					<p>
						<mdn>
							<mrow>	
								\mu(x)\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x) \mu(x) y			\amp = Q(x)	\mu(x)
							</mrow>
							<mrow xml:id="if-method-reversed-product-rule">
								\frac{d}{dx}\left[\mu(x) \cdot y\right]	\amp = Q(x) \mu(x)
							</mrow>
						</mdn>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li xml:id="if-step-3"><title> Step 3: Solve Using Direct Integration </title>
					<p>
						Integrate both sides of equation <xref ref="if-method-reversed-product-rule"/> and solve for <m>y</m> to find the general solution.
					</p>
				</li>
			</dl>
		</exploration>

		<p label="if-method-rq-bundle">
			Answer the general questions about the integrating factor method:
			
			<task label="if-method-cyu-8">
				<title>‚ùìüëâ Checking When the Method Applies </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Which type of equations can always be solved using the IF method?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices randomize="yes">
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>First-order linear equations.</statement>
						<feedback>Correct! That's the specific class this method is designed for.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>First-order separable equations.</statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect. This method only applies to first-order equations.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>Any linear equation.</statement>
						<feedback>Incorrect. This method only applies to first-order equations.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>Any differential equation that contains <m>y</m>.</statement>
						<feedback>Too broad. The method is specific to first-order linear equations.</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="if-method-instep-1">
				<title>‚ùìüëâ Before Finding the Integrating Factor </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
					Suppose you're given the equation:
					<me>2xy' + 4x^2 y = \ln x</me>.
					What should you do before computing an integrating factor?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices randomize="yes">
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>Rewrite the equation in standard form by dividing through by <m>2x</m>.</statement>
						<feedback>Correct! Standard form is required before identifying <m>P(x)</m>.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>Group the left side as a single derivative using the product rule.</statement>
						<feedback>Not quite. Grouping comes after multiplying by the integrating factor.</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Compute the integrating factor.
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The integrating factor depends on <m>P(x)</m>, which must first be identified in standard form.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Integrate both sides of the equation.
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Integration comes after multiplying by the integrating factor.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-if-method-6">
				<title>‚ùìüëâ Multiplying by the Integrating Factor </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Imagine you multiplied this differential equation by its integrating factor.
						<me>
							y' + 2xy = 4x^2
						</me>.
						Which of the following statements is true?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices randomize="yes">
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>The <m>y</m> and <m>y'</m> terms can now be grouped as a single derivative.</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! Multiplying by the integrating factor allows us to rewrite the left-hand side as a single derivative, completing the product rule.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement>The integrating factor is <m>x^2</m>.</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. <m>x^2</m> comes from <m>\int P(x)\ dx</m>, so it is part of the integrating factor, but not the entire integrating factor.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement>
							The solution is equal to the integrating factor.
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The solution is not equal to the integrating factor, but rather, the integrating factor is used to help find the solution.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							The integrating factor is <m>e^{x^2}</m>.
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! The integrating factor is <m>e^{\int 2x\,dx} = e^{x^2}</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-if-method-steps-4">
				<title>‚ùìüëâ Purpose of the Integrating Factor </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Which statement describes the purpose of the multiplying both sides of a differential equation by an integrating factor?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								To eliminate the dependent variable.
							</p>
						</statement>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								To convert the equation into a separable form.
							</p>
						</statement>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								To solve for the constant of integration.
							</p>
						</statement>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								To transform the equation into a direct integration problem.
							</p>
						</statement>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="if-method-examples">
		<title> Full Solutions Using the Method </title>

		<p>
			With the three-step method in hand, we're ready to solve some full equations from start to finish. These examples show how the integrating factor method handles a variety of situations, from clean equations already in standard form to messy ones that need rearranging.
		</p>

		<example label="if-method-example-1">
			<title> Already in Standard Form </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the general solution to the equation
				</p>
				<p>
					<me>
						y' + 6y = 1
					</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					It is already in standard form, so we proceed with the integrating factor method.
				</p>

				<p>
					<xref ref="if-step-1" text="custom">Step 1</xref>. Identify <m>P(x)</m> and compute <m>\mu</m>
					<aside><title>üìå Note</title>
						<p>
							Recall, we ignore the integration constant for the integrating factor.
						</p>
					</aside>
					<me>
						y' + \os{P}{\boxed{6}}\ y = 1\quad \rightarrow \quad \mu(x) = e^{\int 6\ dx} = e^{6x}
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					<xref ref="if-step-2" text="custom">Step 2</xref>. Multiply both sides by <m>e^{6x}</m> to complete the product rule on the left.
					<md>
						<mrow> e^{6x}y' + 6e^{6x}y						\amp = e^{6x}	</mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{d}{dx}\left[e^{6x}\cdot y\right]	\amp = e^{6x}	</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					<xref ref="if-step-3" text="custom">Step 3</xref>, Finally, we integrate:
					<md>
						<mrow> \int \frac{d}{dx}\left[e^{6x}\cdot y\right]\ dx	\amp = \int e^{6x}\ dx			</mrow>
						<mrow> e^{6x}\cdot y									\amp = \frac{1}{6} e^{6x} + c	</mrow>
						<mrow> y												\amp = \frac{1}{6} + ce^{-6x}.	</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<example label="if-method-example-2">
			<title> Rearranging to Standard Form </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the equation
				</p>
				<p>
					<me>x^2y' = 5x^3 + 2x^3y </me>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					This equation is first-order and linear, but not in standard form, so we  divide both sides by <m>x^2</m> and move the <m>y</m> to the same side as the <m>y'</m> term:
					<me>
						y' = 5x + 2x y \quad \Rightarrow \quad y' - 2x y = 5x
					</me>.
					Now the IF method applies.
				</p>

				<p>
					<xref ref="if-step-1" text="custom">Step 1</xref>. Identify <m>P(x)</m> and compute <m>\mu</m>:
					<me>
						y' + \os{P}{\boxed{-2x}} y = 5x \quad \rightarrow \quad \mu = e^{\int -2x\ dx} = e^{-x^2}
					</me>.
				</p>

				<p>
					<xref ref="if-step-2" text="custom">Step 2</xref>. Multiply by <m>e^{-x^2}</m> to complete the product rule on the left:
					<md>
						<mrow> e^{-x^2}y' - 2x e^{-x^2}y				\amp = 5xe^{-x^2}	</mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{d}{dx}\left[e^{-x^2}\cdot y\right]	\amp = 5xe^{-x^2}	</mrow>
					</md>.
				</p>

				<p>
					<xref ref="if-step-3" text="custom">Step 3</xref>. Here, the integral on the right is computed with <m>u</m>-substitution:
				</p>

				<sidebyside widths="60% 20%" margins="10% 10%" valign="top">
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> \int \frac{d}{dx}\left[e^{-x^2}\cdot y\right]dx	\amp = \int 5xe^{-x^2}dx		</mrow>
							<mrow> e^{-x^2}\cdot y									\amp = -\frac52 \int e^{u}du	</mrow>
							<mrow> e^{-x^2}\cdot y									\amp = -\frac52 e^{u} + c		</mrow>
							<mrow> e^{-x^2}\cdot y									\amp = -\frac52 e^{-x^2} + c	</mrow>
							<mrow> y												\amp = -\frac52 + ce^{x^2}		</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow> u = -x^2</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>
				

				<solution><title> Verify the Solution </title>
					
					<p>
						We have found the general solution, but it is worth remembering that we can verify our solution by substituting back into the original equation.
					</p>

					<sidebyside>
						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\ul{LHS}														</mrow>
								<mrow>	x^2y'															</mrow>
								<mrow>	x^2 \cdot \frac{d}{dx}\left( -\frac{5}{2} + ce^{x^2} \right)	</mrow>
								<mrow>	x^2 \cdot \left( 0 + 2cxe^{x^2} \right)							</mrow>
								<mrow>	2c x^3 e^{x^2}	\quad‚úÖ											</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>

						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\ul{RHS}											</mrow>
								<mrow>	5x^3 + 2x^3y										</mrow>
								<mrow>	5x^3 + 2x^3\left( -\frac{5}{2} + ce^{x^2} \right)	</mrow>
								<mrow>	5x^3 - 5x^3+ 2c x^3 e^{x^2}							</mrow>
								<mrow>	2c x^3 e^{x^2}	\quad‚úÖ								</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
					
					<p>
						The same result on the left &amp; right confirms our solution.
					</p>
				</solution>

			</solution>
		</example>

		<example label="if-method-example-3">
			<title> Requires Integration by Parts </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the equation:
					<me> t^2 y' + 2ty = t^3 \ln t </me>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Put the equation in standard form, identify <m>P(x)</m>, and compute <m>\mu</m>:
				</p>

				<me>
					y' + \us{P}{\boxed{\frac{2}{t}}}\ y = t \ln t \quad \implies \quad
					\mu(t) = e^{\large \int (\sfrac{2}{t})\, dt} = e^{2 \ln t} = t^2
				</me>
			
				<p>
					Multiply by <m>e^{1/x}</m> and reverse the product rule on the left side.
					<md>
						<mrow> t^2 y' + 2t y					\amp = t^3 \ln t	</mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{d}{dt} \left[t^2 y\right]	\amp = t^3 \ln t	</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			
				<p>
					Now, integrate both sides and use <xref ref="ibp-formula" text="custom">integration by parts</xref> on the right.
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="3% 60% 35% 2%" valigns="top top top top">

						<p/>
						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\int \frac{d}{dt} \big[t^2 y\big] dt \amp = \int t^3 \ln t\ dt
								</mrow>
								<mrow>	
									t^2 y	=
									\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{ u}}{\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange} \uparrow}{\ul{\vphantom{\frac11}\ln t}}}
									\cdot
									\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{ v}}{\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange} \uparrow}{\ul{\frac14 t^4}}}
									\amp\ - \int
									\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{ v}}{\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange} \uparrow}{\ul{\frac14 t^4}}}
									\cdot
									\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{du}}{\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange} \uparrow}{\ul{\frac{1}{t}\ dt}}}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>	t^2 y	= \frac14 t^4 \ln t \amp\ - \frac14 \int  t^3\ dt					</mrow>
								<mrow>	t^2 y	= \frac{t^4}{4} \ln t \amp\ - \frac{t^4}{16} + c						</mrow>
								<mrow>		y	= \frac{t^2}{4} \ln t \amp\ - \frac{t^2}{16} + c\,t^2				</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>
						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	\small\textcolor{BurntOrange}{				u = \ln t,}	\amp \ \ \small\textcolor{BurntOrange}{v = \frac14t^4}	</mrow>
								<mrow>	\small\textcolor{BurntOrange}{	du = \frac{1}{t}\ dt,}	\amp \ \ \small\textcolor{BurntOrange}{dv = t^3\ dt}	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>
						<p/>

					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					Finally, solve for <m>y</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow>	y = \frac{t^2}{4} \ln t - \frac{t^2}{16} + c\,t^2	</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<example label="if-method-example-4">
			<title> An Initial-Valued Problem </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Solve the initial value problem.
					<me>
						A = \sec\theta A' - \frac{\theta e^{\large\theta^2 + \sin\theta}}{\cos \theta}, \hspace{1cm} A(0) = -\frac{1}{2}
					</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					Put the equation in standard form by replacing <m>\sec\theta</m> with <m>\frac{1}{\cos\theta}</m> and moving the <m>A'</m> term to the left:
				</p>

				<me>
					\frac{1}{\cos\theta} A' - A = \frac{\theta e^{\large\theta^2 + \sin\theta}}{\cos \theta}
				</me>.

				<p>
					Multiplying this by <m>\cos\theta</m> allows us to identify <m>P</m> and compute <m>\mu</m>:
					<me>
						A' + \us{P}{\boxed{- \cos\theta}}\ A = \theta e^{\large \theta^2 + \sin\theta}
						\quad \implies \quad
						\mu = e\vphantom{\large|}^{\large\int -\cos\theta d\theta} = e^{\large -\sin\theta}
					</me>
				</p>

				<p>
					Multiply by <m>e^{1/x}</m> and complete the product rule on the left side.
					<md>
						<mrow> e^{\large -\sin\theta}A' - \cos\theta e^{\large -\sin\theta}A = \theta e^{\large\theta^2 + \sin\theta}	</mrow>
						<mrow> \frac{d}{d\theta}\left[ e^{\large -\sin\theta}A \right] = \theta e^{\large\theta^2}	</mrow>
					</md>.
				</p>
			
				<p>
					Integrate both sides and use <m>u</m>-substitution:
				</p>

				<p>
					<sidebyside widths="10% 60% 25% 5%" valigns="top top top top">

						<p/>
						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\int \frac{d}{d\theta}\left[ e^{\large -\sin\theta}A \right] d\theta = \int \theta e^{\large\theta^2} d\theta
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									e^{\large -\sin\theta}A = \frac{1}{2}e^{\large\theta^2} + c
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									A = \frac{1}{2}e^{\large\theta^2 + \sin\theta} + ce^{\large\sin\theta}
								</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>
						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>	u	\amp = \theta^2			</mrow>
								<mrow>	du	\amp = 2\theta\ d\theta	</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>
						<p/>

					</sidebyside>

				</p>

				<p>
					Finally, we apply the initial condition to determine the constant <m>c</m>.
					<md>
						<mrow> -\frac{1}{2} = A(0) \amp = \frac{1}{2}e^{\large 0^2 + \sin(0)} + ce^{\large\sin(0)}	</mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp = \frac{1}{2}e^0 + ce^0 	</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2} + c\quad \implies \quad c = -1	</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					We can then write the particular solution to the initial value problem.
					<me>A(\theta) = \frac{1}{2}e^{\large\theta^2 + \sin\theta} - e^{\large\sin\theta}</me>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<p>
			These examples demonstrate the versatility of the <em>Integrating Factor Method</em>. Regardless of the complexity of the given equation, this <em>three-step approach</em> provides a reliable solution strategy for <em>any</em> first-order linear differential equation.
		</p>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs label="if-method-wrapup">
		<title> üóùÔ∏è Key Takeaways </title>
		<p>
			<aside><title>üéß Listen</title><p><audio source="audio/readings/c1/template.mp3" width="100%" /></p></aside>
			<ul marker="square">
				<li>
					The integrating factor method is a structured process for solving first-order linear differential equations of the form <m>y' + P(x)y = Q(x)</m>.
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						The method involves three steps:
						<ol marker="(1)">
							<li>compute the integrating factor <m>\mu(x) = e^{\int P(x)\,dx}</m> and multiply onto the equation,</li>
							<li>this completes the product rule for reversal back into its pre-applied form,</li>
							<li>integrate both sides to find the solution <m>y</m>.</li>
						</ol>
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					Multiplying by the integrating factor allows the left-hand side to be written as a single derivative, which can be easily solved by integration.
				</li>
				<li>
					The process always works on first-order linear equations, regardless of how messy the original equation looks, as long as it can be rewritten in standard form.
				</li>
			</ul>
		</p>
	</paragraphs>
	
